<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Slope_picture.svg" class="image" title="The slope of a line is defined as the rise over the run, m = Δy / Δx."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Slope_picture.svg/180px-Slope_picture.svg.png" width="180" height="237" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Slope_picture.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
The slope of a line is defined as the rise over the run, <span class="texhtml"><i>m</i> = Δ<i>y</i> / Δ<i>x</i>.</span></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Slope</b> is used to describe the steepness, incline, gradient, or <a href="/wiki/Grade_(slope)" title="Grade (slope)">grade</a> of a <a href="/wiki/Line_(mathematics)" title="Line (mathematics)" class="mw-redirect">straight line</a>. A higher slope value indicates a steeper incline. The slope is defined as the ratio of the "<b>rise</b>" divided by the "<b>run</b>" between two points on a line, or in other words, the ratio of the altitude change to the horizontal distance between any two points on the line. It is also always the same thing as how many rises in one run.</p>
<p>Using <a href="/wiki/Calculus" title="Calculus">calculus</a>, one can calculate the slope of the <a href="/wiki/Tangent" title="Tangent">tangent</a> to a <a href="/wiki/Curve" title="Curve">curve</a> at a point.</p>
<p>The concept of slope, and much of this article, applies directly to <a href="/wiki/Grade_(slope)" title="Grade (slope)">grades</a> or <a href="/wiki/Gradient" title="Gradient">gradients</a> in <a href="/wiki/Geography" title="Geography">geography</a> and <a href="/wiki/Civil_engineering" title="Civil engineering">civil engineering</a>.</p>
